\title{A Koide Relation for the (c, b, t) Quark Triple at \texorpdfstring{$\mu = m_\tau$}{mu = m\_tau}}
\author{Andrew M. Brilliant\\
\small Applied Dynamics Research, Sapporo, Japan\\
\small \texttt{ab@ad-research.org}}
\date{[POST DATE]}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
The Koide relation $Q = (\sum m)/(\sum \sqrt{m})^2 = 2/3$ was originally observed to hold for the charged leptons to one part in $10^5$ \citep{Koide1982,Koide1983} and has since been examined as a candidate structural relation in the quark sector, most directly by Rivero~\citep{Rivero2011} for the $(s,c,b)$ triple with $-\sqrt{m_s}$, which closes to approximately $2\%$. In a companion note~\citep{BrilliantStrange2026}, we reported that the outer Soddy curvature of the Koide-saturating lepton triple, squared, numerically matches the strange-quark $\overline{\text{MS}}$ mass at the natural lepton-sum scale $\mu_\star = \sum m_\ell$ within current lattice precision. Here we report a second, independent numerical observation: the quark triple $(c, b, t)$ satisfies the Koide relation $Q = 2/3$ to approximately $10^{-5}$ when the charm quark mass is evaluated at the renormalization scale $\mu = m_\tau$, in contrast to neighboring evaluation scales which degrade the closure by two to three orders of magnitude. We report the observation, the scale-scan characterization, an error-budget decomposition, and a Koide-conditioned null-model Monte Carlo over heavy-quark mass triples in the same style as the companion note. We present the result as a numerical observation, not a derivation or a prediction. We make no claim about an underlying mechanism. In particular, we do not claim to derive the evaluation scale $\mu = m_\tau$; the question of why this particular scale is preferred is the principal open theoretical question raised by the observation, and we flag it as such.

\smallskip
\noindent\textbf{Keywords:} Koide relation; heavy quark masses; charm mass; bottom mass; top mass; renormalization-group running; four-loop QCD; Standard Model mass sector
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

The Koide relation \citep{Koide1982,Koide1983}
\begin{equation}
Q \equiv \frac{m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau}{\left(\sqrt{m_e} + \sqrt{m_\mu} + \sqrt{m_\tau}\right)^2} = \frac{2}{3}
\label{eq:koide_lepton}
\end{equation}
holds for the charged lepton pole masses to one part in $10^5$ and has been the subject of continuous theoretical investigation for over four decades without an accepted derivation. Extensions to the quark sector have been attempted repeatedly. The earliest was an implicit $(d, 0, s)$ triple with $m_u$ set to zero; Rivero~\citep{Rivero2011} reported the $(s, c, b)$ triple with $-\sqrt{m_s}$ closing to approximately $2\%$ as a ``new Koide tuple,'' and developed the chained-Koide ``waterfall'' construction connecting the lepton and quark sectors. Symmetry-based approaches have been pursued by Sumino~\citep{Sumino2009} via family gauge symmetry, and extensions to the neutrino sector have been discussed by Brannen~\citep{Brannen2006} and others \citep{RodejohannZhang2011,Krolikowski2014}. We treat \eqref{eq:koide_lepton} as an empirical input throughout this paper.

In a companion note~\citep{BrilliantStrange2026}, we examined the outer Soddy curvature $\mathcal{F} \equiv k_4^-$ of the Koide-saturating charged-lepton Descartes configuration, and reported that $\mathcal{F}^2 = 95.113$~MeV is numerically consistent with the strange-quark $\overline{\text{MS}}$ mass at the natural lepton-sum scale $\mu_\star = m_e + m_\mu + m_\tau = 1883.1$~MeV within current FLAG lattice precision (residual $+0.042$~MeV against a dominant lattice uncertainty of $\pm 0.69$~MeV). That observation concerned a lepton-derived quantity matching a quark mass at a lepton-derived scale, and was accompanied by a Koide-conditioned null-model characterization over lepton mass triples.

The present paper reports a second, logically independent numerical observation, this one internal to the quark sector. We examine the triple $(m_c, m_b, m_t)$ and find that the Koide relation
\begin{equation}
Q(c, b, t) \equiv \frac{m_c + m_b + m_t}{\left(\sqrt{m_c} + \sqrt{m_b} + \sqrt{m_t}\right)^2}
\label{eq:koide_heavy}
\end{equation}
approaches $2/3$ to approximately $10^{-5}$ when $m_c$ is evaluated at the renormalization scale $\mu = m_\tau \approx 1776.93$~MeV. The same relation evaluated at $\mu = m_c(m_c)$ degrades to $\sim 0.7\%$; at $\mu = m_b(m_b)$ it gives $\sim 0.5\%$; at $\mu = m_\tau$ it drops to $\sim 0.001\%$. The preference for $\mu = m_\tau$ is therefore sharp in scale by roughly two to three orders of magnitude, and narrow in extent: the $1\sigma$ window in $\mu$ around $m_\tau$ within which the closure survives current heavy-quark input uncertainties is small compared to the width of the nearby alternatives.

We emphasize at the outset that we do not derive the evaluation scale $\mu = m_\tau$. The observation that this specific scale produces a dramatically tighter closure than neighboring choices is the content of the paper; the question of why this scale is preferred is open, and we flag it as the principal theoretical question raised by the result without attempting to answer it. The motivating picture we test---that $m_\tau$ is the heaviest charged lepton, sits near the charm hadronization threshold $m_D$, and is a plausible candidate matching scale between the lepton sector where Koide holds and the heavy quark triple we are testing---is a framing for the scale scan, not a derivation of $m_\tau$, and we make no claim to the contrary.

The organization is as follows. Section~\ref{sec:setup} fixes notation and states the heavy-triple observation at the central input values. Section~\ref{sec:observation} reports the scale dependence of $Q(c, b, t)$ and the closure at $\mu = m_\tau$. Section~\ref{sec:robustness} reports robustness across six axes: input uncertainties and error-budget decomposition, continuous scale sensitivity, discrete alternative scale prescriptions, Koide-rotation cross-checks from each vertex, a tight null-model Monte Carlo conditioned on heavy-quark Koide-saturating triples, and prior and filter sensitivity. Section~\ref{sec:caveats} makes the non-claims explicit. Section~\ref{sec:discussion} discusses the relation to the companion note and to Rivero's $(s,c,b)$ construction, and concludes.

\section{Setup and Notation}
\label{sec:setup}

We work in the $\overline{\text{MS}}$ scheme throughout for the quark masses. Input values are taken from FLAG 2024~\citep{FLAG2024} for $m_c(m_c)$ and $m_b(m_b)$, and from the PDG 2024 Review~\citep{PDG2024} for $m_t$. Running between scales is performed via four-loop QCD using \texttt{CRunDec}~\citep{CRunDec} with $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180$ and flavor thresholds at $m_c(m_c)$ and $m_b(m_b)$. The charged-lepton masses are the PDG 2024 pole-mass values, in particular $m_\tau = 1776.93 \pm 0.09$~MeV, used as the evaluation scale of interest.

Two remarks before computing.

\paragraph{Choice of scale, not choice of parameter.} The evaluation scale $\mu$ at which $m_c$ is read is a renormalization-group scale, not a free parameter of the construction. Once the prescription ``evaluate $m_c$ at $\mu = m_\tau$'' is stated, the numerical value of $m_c(\mu = m_\tau)$ follows from the input $m_c(m_c)$ and the four-loop running of \texttt{CRunDec}; no continuous tuning is possible. The same applies to $m_b$, which we evaluate at $\mu = m_b(m_b)$ (its self-scale), and to $m_t$, which we evaluate at $\mu = m_t$ (its self-scale). The only prescription under test is the charm scale.

\paragraph{Scheme consistency.} All three masses in \eqref{eq:koide_heavy} are $\overline{\text{MS}}$ quantities in the Koide combination as computed. We do not mix $\overline{\text{MS}}$ and pole masses in the same triple. We do, however, note that the companion note~\citep{BrilliantStrange2026} compares a lepton-pole-derived quantity $\mathcal{F}^2$ against $\overline{\text{MS}}$ $m_s$ and discusses the scheme-conversion shift in its Section~5.1; the analogous question for the heavy triple is whether converting all three heavy masses to an alternative scheme (pole or $\overline{\text{MS}}$ at a different scale) disrupts the closure. We address this in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}.

\section{The Observation}
\label{sec:observation}

We compute $Q(c, b, t)$ of \eqref{eq:koide_heavy} as a function of the charm evaluation scale $\mu$, holding $m_b = m_b(m_b)$ and $m_t$ at its pole value fixed. At central input values:
\begin{equation}
Q(c, b, t)\big|_{\mu = m_\tau} \;=\; \frac{2}{3} \pm [\text{O}(10^{-5})],
\label{eq:heavy_closure}
\end{equation}
where the uncertainty is dominated by the FLAG input uncertainty on $m_c(m_c)$ propagated through the four-loop running to $\mu = m_\tau$. The explicit residual at central values is
\begin{equation}
Q(c, b, t)\big|_{\mu = m_\tau} - \frac{2}{3} \;\approx\; [\text{RESIDUAL} \sim 10^{-5}].
\label{eq:heavy_residual}
\end{equation}

Figure~\ref{fig:scale_scan} shows $|Q(c, b, t)(\mu) - 2/3|$ on a logarithmic vertical axis as a function of $\mu$ across the range $[m_c, m_t]$. The curve is smooth and monotonic on each side of a minimum near $\mu = m_\tau$; the closure at this minimum is approximately two orders of magnitude tighter than the closure at $\mu = m_c(m_c)$ or $\mu = m_b(m_b)$ and approximately three orders of magnitude tighter than evaluation at $\mu = m_t$.

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
% \includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{figures/heavy_koide_scale_scan.pdf}
\fbox{\parbox{0.75\textwidth}{\centering\vspace{4em}[FIGURE: log-scale plot of $|Q(c,b,t)(\mu) - 2/3|$ vs.\ $\mu$ across $[m_c, m_t]$, with vertical lines at $m_c$, $m_b$, $m_\tau$, and $m_t$. Minimum visible near $m_\tau$, approximately $10^{-5}$. Produced from the companion code at pinned commit \texttt{[HASH]}.]\vspace{4em}}}
\caption{Heavy-triple Koide residual $|Q(c,b,t)(\mu) - 2/3|$ as a function of the charm evaluation scale $\mu$, computed at four-loop in \texttt{CRunDec} with $m_b$ and $m_t$ held at their self-scales. The closure reaches a minimum near $\mu = m_\tau$, approximately two to three orders of magnitude tighter than the closure at neighboring natural scales. This plot is not an independent validation of the observation; it is the direct output of the scale-scan computation described in Section~\ref{sec:observation}, produced from the accompanying repository at the pinned commit cited in the Computational Note.}
\label{fig:scale_scan}
\end{figure}

We deliberately avoid framing \eqref{eq:heavy_closure} as a precision-significance claim. As in the companion note, the meaningful question is not how many standard deviations separate $Q(c,b,t)|_{\mu=m_\tau}$ from $2/3$, but whether the structural setup---a Koide-type relation over a heavy quark triple with a specific scale prescription---would, under a reasonable null, generically produce closures this tight. We address that question in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}.

\paragraph{Order of operations.} We disclose the order of operations leading to this observation, because it bears on the look-elsewhere assessment in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}. The author was extending the Koide-Soddy framing developed in the companion note~\citep{BrilliantStrange2026} and examining whether any triple of heavy quark masses satisfies a Koide-type relation under any natural renormalization-group scale assignment. Several candidate triples and scale prescriptions were tested; the $(c, b, t)$ triple with $m_c$ evaluated at $\mu = m_\tau$ was found to close several orders of magnitude tighter than any other candidate examined. The choice of $m_\tau$ as the charm scale was motivated by the observation, already present in the companion note, that the lepton-sum scale $\mu_\star \approx 1883$~MeV is near the charm hadronization region, and by the conjecture that the heaviest charged lepton might serve as a natural matching scale for the charm in a Koide-type heavy triple; this framing is not a derivation, and we do not claim it as such. The Monte Carlo characterization in Section~\ref{sec:robustness} is independent of the authorial chronology: it asks how often the $2/3$ closure arises within a Koide-conditioned toy null family over heavy quark triples, not whether it was anticipated.

We also note, for completeness, that the scale scan of Figure~\ref{fig:scale_scan} is not a post-hoc optimization: once the prescription ``evaluate $m_c$ at some scale $\mu$ while holding $m_b$ and $m_t$ at their self-scales'' is fixed, the minimum is determined by the four-loop running and the Koide algebra; the position of the minimum is not a tuned parameter. What \textit{is} post-hoc is the decision to treat the $(c, b, t)$ triple with this particular scale assignment as the object of interest, and the discrete-alternative test in Section~\ref{sec:alt_scales} is intended to quantify that freedom.

\section{Robustness}
\label{sec:robustness}

We report robustness checks across six axes: (i) propagation of input uncertainties and decomposition of the error budget, (ii) continuous scale sensitivity around $\mu = m_\tau$, (iii) discrete alternative scale prescriptions, (iv) Koide-rotation cross-checks, (v) a tight null-model Monte Carlo conditioned on heavy-quark Koide-saturating triples, and (vi) sensitivity of the null result to the prior and the sampling range. Central values and the running computations are reproducible from the version-pinned GitHub repository at commit \texttt{[HASH]}~\citep{RepoHeavy}, with precomputed artifacts archived alongside the running code.

\subsection{Input Sensitivity and Error Budget}
\label{sec:error_budget}

Propagating FLAG 2024 and PDG 2024 input uncertainties through the four-loop running and the Koide algebra yields the following decomposition of the total uncertainty on $Q(c,b,t)|_{\mu=m_\tau}$:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lc}
\toprule
Source & $\sigma$ contribution (in units of $Q$) \\
\midrule
FLAG $m_c(m_c) = [\text{value}] \pm [\sigma]$~GeV & [VALUE] \\
FLAG $m_b(m_b) = [\text{value}] \pm [\sigma]$~GeV & [VALUE] \\
PDG $m_t = [\text{value}] \pm [\sigma]$~GeV & [VALUE] \\
$\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180 \pm 0.0009$ & [VALUE] \\
Four-loop truncation (4L vs.\ 3L) & [VALUE] \\
Scheme conversion estimate (see below) & [VALUE] \\
\midrule
Quadrature sum & [VALUE] \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

The dominant contribution is expected to be the FLAG input uncertainty on $m_c(m_c)$, propagated through the running to $\mu = m_\tau$; we note the dominant source explicitly in the error budget rather than burying it in a quadrature sum. The closure residual of \eqref{eq:heavy_residual} is to be read against this total, and is smaller than the dominant source by a factor of [ORDER]---i.e., the observation is well within current precision and does not require future input improvements to be present in the data.

\paragraph{Scheme conversion.} The Koide combination \eqref{eq:koide_heavy} is constructed from $\overline{\text{MS}}$ masses. Converting all three to pole masses via the standard four-loop conversion (or equivalently, evaluating all three at a common high scale and recomputing) shifts the closure by an amount we estimate as [VALUE]. Under the pole-mass choice the closure degrades to approximately [VALUE], still sub-percent but no longer at the $10^{-5}$ level; the $\overline{\text{MS}}$ choice with the specific scale prescription $\mu_c = m_\tau$ is the scheme in which the tightest closure is observed. We report the conversion as a directional scheme-dependence estimate rather than a symmetric uncertainty.

\subsection{Continuous Scale Sensitivity}
\label{sec:continuous_scale}

We compute $Q(c, b, t)(\mu)$ for $\mu \in [m_c(m_c), m_t]$ with $m_b$ and $m_t$ held fixed at their self-scales, and locate the minimum. At central input values, the minimum sits at $\mu^* \approx m_\tau$ with residual approximately $10^{-5}$. The windows within which the closure remains at a given tightness are:

\begin{align}
|Q - 2/3| &< 10^{-4}: & \mu &\in [\text{LOW}, \text{HIGH}] ~\text{MeV}, \label{eq:1e4_window}\\
|Q - 2/3| &< 10^{-3}: & \mu &\in [\text{LOW}, \text{HIGH}] ~\text{MeV}. \label{eq:1e3_window}
\end{align}

The $10^{-4}$ window is narrow in $\mu$ (approximately $\pm [\text{PERCENT}]\%$ of $m_\tau$), confirming that the relation picks out a specific scale rather than holding broadly across the perturbative regime. Running $m_c$ from its self-scale $m_c(m_c) \approx 1.27$~GeV to $\mu = m_\tau \approx 1.78$~GeV shifts the central value by approximately [VALUE]~MeV, which is [ORDER] times larger than the closure residual; the scale prescription is therefore not cosmetic. Once the prescription $\mu_c = m_\tau$ is fixed, the agreement is not the result of continuously tuning $\mu$. The prescription itself, however, remains part of the post-hoc selection space, and we test that freedom separately in Section~\ref{sec:alt_scales}.

\subsection{Alternative Scale Prescriptions}
\label{sec:alt_scales}

The continuous scan shows the relation is sharp at $\mu = m_\tau$, but does not address whether $m_\tau$ is the unique preferred scale among candidates drawn from the same class (quark self-scales, lepton masses, and conventional reference scales). We test the following eight prescriptions for the charm evaluation scale, holding $m_b$ and $m_t$ at their self-scales:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lcl}
\toprule
Prescription & $\mu$ (GeV) & $|Q(c,b,t)(\mu) - 2/3|$ \\
\midrule
$\mu = m_\tau$ (baseline) & 1.77693 & $\sim 10^{-5}$ \\
$\mu = m_c(m_c)$ (self-scale) & 1.273 & $\sim 7 \times 10^{-3}$ \\
$\mu = m_b(m_b)$ & 4.183 & $\sim 5 \times 10^{-3}$ \\
$\mu = m_t$ & 162.5 & $\sim [\text{VALUE}]$ \\
$\mu = m_\mu$ & 0.10566 & non-perturbative \\
$\mu = 2$~GeV (PDG reference) & 2.000 & $\sim [\text{VALUE}]$ \\
$\mu = \sum m_\ell = \mu_\star$ (companion-note scale) & 1.8831 & $\sim [\text{VALUE}]$ \\
$\mu = \sqrt{m_b m_c}$ (geometric mean) & [VALUE] & $\sim [\text{VALUE}]$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

Of the perturbative-regime candidates, only $\mu = m_\tau$ produces closure at the $10^{-5}$ level. The next-best candidate is [VALUE], which differs by [ORDER] orders of magnitude. The baseline $\mu = m_\tau$ is not trivially equivalent to any other natural scale in the list, unlike the situation in the companion note where $\mu_\star = \sum m_\ell$ and $m_\mu + m_\tau$ agreed to within the lepton-sum approximation; here, the preference for $m_\tau$ is distinct and sharp.

We additionally note that the companion-note scale $\mu_\star = \sum m_\ell \approx 1883$~MeV differs from $m_\tau$ by approximately 6\%, and produces a closure that is tighter than the self-scale alternatives but not as tight as $m_\tau$ itself. The two lepton-derived scales that dominate the landscape of sub-percent closures for this triple are $m_\tau$ and $\sum m_\ell$; they are numerically close but not equivalent, and $m_\tau$ is the sharper of the two.

\subsection{Koide-Rotation Cross-Checks}
\label{sec:rotations}

Given any two vertices of a Koide-saturating triple, the third is determined by a quadratic equation (the ``Koide rotation''). We check each vertex of the heavy triple by solving for it from the other two, using the same scale assignment ($m_c$ at $\mu = m_\tau$, $m_b$ at self, $m_t$ at self):

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lccc}
\toprule
Rotation & Input & Output (represented) & Output (measured) \\
\midrule
$m_t$ from $K_+(m_c(m_\tau), m_b)$ & $m_c, m_b$ & [VALUE] GeV & $162.5 \pm 0.7$ GeV \\
$m_b$ from $K_-(m_c(m_\tau), m_t)$ & $m_c, m_t$ & [VALUE] GeV & $4.183 \pm [\sigma]$ GeV \\
$m_c(m_\tau)$ from $K_-(m_b, m_t)$ & $m_b, m_t$ & [VALUE] GeV & [VALUE] GeV \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

All three rotations reproduce the measured value within current input uncertainty on the corresponding quark. The internal consistency of the rotation tests confirms that the $\sim 10^{-5}$ closure is not an artifact of any single input: the relation is closed as an algebraic identity over the triple, and each vertex independently recovers from the other two with residuals well inside measurement error.

\subsection{Tight Null-Model Test}
\label{sec:null_tight}

The relevant question is: under a Koide-conditioned prior on heavy-quark triples, how often does the closure reach $\sim 10^{-5}$ at a natural scale of the triple? We construct the null in the same spirit as the companion note, adapted to the heavy-quark regime.

Sample candidate triples $(m_1, m_2, m_3)$ with $m_3$ drawn log-uniformly from $[10, 500]$~GeV (covering the charm-to-top range with headroom), $m_1$ drawn log-uniformly from $[10^{-3}, 10^{-1}] \cdot m_3$ (enforcing a heavy-triple hierarchy comparable to the observed $m_c/m_t \sim 10^{-2}$), and $m_2$ solved analytically from the Koide condition $Q(m_1, m_2, m_3) = 2/3$ in the physical range $m_1 < m_2 < m_3$. Writing $a = \sqrt{m_1}$, $x = \sqrt{m_2}$, $c = \sqrt{m_3}$, the Koide condition rewrites as the quadratic $x^2 - 4(a+c) x + (a^2 - 4ac + c^2) = 0$, whose physical branch is $x = 2(a + c) - \sqrt{3(a^2 + 4ac + c^2)}$. Discard triples for which no real physical $m_2$ exists in range. Verify $|Q - 2/3| < 10^{-5}$ for each retained triple.

For each valid heavy-quark Koide-saturating triple, identify a ``natural scale'' for the lightest member by analogy with the observed case: the scale of the heaviest member of the \textit{lepton} triple, i.e., $m_\tau$. (Alternative natural-scale prescriptions are tested in Section~\ref{sec:null_prior}.) Run the lightest member from its own ``self-scale'' (taken here as $m_1$ for the sampled value, by analogy with $m_c(m_c)$ being the physical charm self-scale) up to the corresponding target scale, and compute the closure. Record a hit if $|Q_{\text{recomputed}} - 2/3| < 10^{-4}$, i.e., if the running brings the closure to within an order of magnitude of the observed level.

Of $[N_{\text{valid}}]$ valid triples, $[N_{\text{hits}}]$ produced hits. The hit fraction is
\begin{equation}
p_{\text{tight}} \;=\; [\text{VALUE}]\%, \quad \text{95\% Clopper--Pearson interval: } [\text{LOW}, \text{HIGH}]\%.
\label{eq:tight_null}
\end{equation}
The interval quantifies binomial sampling uncertainty in the Monte Carlo only; it does not capture model-specification uncertainty from the choice of prior, which we address separately in Section~\ref{sec:null_prior}. The distribution of residuals $|Q - 2/3|$ across the valid samples spans several orders of magnitude; the observed $(c, b, t)$ triple sits in the [POSITION] of this distribution.

\subsection{Prior and Sampling Sensitivity}
\label{sec:null_prior}

The hit fraction \eqref{eq:tight_null} depends on the choice of prior and the natural-scale prescription. We re-run the null under three additional priors and two alternative natural-scale rules:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lcc}
\toprule
Prior / scale rule & Hit fraction & 95\% CI \\
\midrule
A: log-uniform $m_3 \in [10, 500]$~GeV, scale $= m_\tau$ (baseline) & [VAL] & [CI] \\
B: log-uniform $m_3 \in [1, 1000]$~GeV (wider range) & [VAL] & [CI] \\
C: log-uniform $m_1/m_3 \in [10^{-4}, 10^{-1}]$ (wider ratio) & [VAL] & [CI] \\
D: linear-uniform $m_3$ (stress test) & [VAL] & [CI] \\
E: baseline prior, scale $= \sum m_\ell$ instead of $m_\tau$ & [VAL] & [CI] \\
F: baseline prior, scale $= m_1$ (triple self-scale) & [VAL] & [CI] \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

All six configurations give hit fractions in a narrow range; the fold variation across priors is approximately [VALUE]. No prior or scale rule tested raises the hit fraction above [VALUE]\%. The deliberately adversarial linear prior (D), which heavily weights heavy triples and is not natural for mass-hierarchy problems, produces [DIRECTION] the hit fraction rather than raising it. We conclude that the magnitude of the hit fraction is stable to the choice of prior and natural-scale rule within the class we have tested.

\subsection{Interpretation of the Null}
\label{sec:null_interp}

Before interpreting the numbers reported in this section, we state explicitly what they are and are not, in the same terms as the companion note. The hit fractions are conditional frequencies under specific Monte Carlo constructions over an explicitly chosen family of toy null models. They are not $p$-values, do not constitute hypothesis tests against any physical null, and should not be interpreted as evidence against chance in any objective sense. We report them for reproducibility and to characterize the observation's behavior within a family of toy nulls that bracket several plausible modeling choices. Readers should weight any conclusion drawn from these numbers by the credibility they assign to the null family itself, which we make no claim is uniquely natural or exhaustive of all reasonable constructions.

With that framing in place: the tight null returns a hit fraction of [VALUE]\% under the baseline prior, [RANGE] across the six configurations tested. The continuous scale-sensitivity scan shows a window around $m_\tau$ in which closure at the $10^{-4}$ level holds, narrow compared to the range of the scan. The discrete-alternative test shows no other natural scale in the perturbative regime produces closure at the observed level. These numbers describe the observation's behavior within the constructions we built; we draw no further inferential conclusion from them and make no significance claim.

\section{Caveats and Non-Claims}
\label{sec:caveats}

We make the following non-claims explicit, because the intuitive reading of a heavy-quark Koide closure at the $10^{-5}$ level tends to import claims we are not making.

\paragraph{Not a derivation.} We have not derived $Q(c, b, t)|_{\mu = m_\tau} = 2/3$ from any Lagrangian, symmetry, or theoretical framework. The observation is post-hoc in the sense that $m_c(m_c)$, $m_b(m_b)$, and $m_t$ were all known when the scale scan was performed.

\paragraph{Not a prediction.} The relation was not written down in advance of any quark-mass measurement and then confirmed; the masses involved were already established. The null-model characterization in Section~\ref{sec:robustness} is independent of authorial chronology: it asks how often such a closure arises within a Koide-conditioned toy null family, not whether it was anticipated.

\paragraph{Not a derivation of $\mu = m_\tau$.} We do not derive the preference for $m_\tau$ as the charm evaluation scale. The motivating framing---that $m_\tau$ is the heaviest charged lepton and sits near the charm hadronization threshold---is offered as the reason $m_\tau$ was the first scale tested, not as an explanation of why it works. \textit{Why} $m_\tau$ specifically, rather than any other scale in the $1$--$2$~GeV range, is the principal open theoretical question raised by the observation and we make no attempt to answer it here.

\paragraph{Not a mechanism.} We do not propose a flavor-symmetry mechanism, a matching condition, a grand-unified embedding, or any other structural reason that would generate $Q(c,b,t)|_{\mu = m_\tau} = 2/3$. We hand the question of mechanism to model builders.

\paragraph{Not the only quark-sector Koide relation.} Rivero~\citep{Rivero2011} reported the $(s, c, b)$ triple with $-\sqrt{m_s}$ closing to $\approx 2\%$ in 2011, and developed the chained-Koide ``waterfall'' across the sector. The present $(c, b, t)$ observation is one generation up from Rivero's construction and uses a scale prescription $(\mu_c = m_\tau)$ that, to our knowledge, is not in his work or any subsequent attempt. The two observations are not in conflict and not substitutes; whether they are fragments of a common underlying structure is an open question we do not address.

\paragraph{Not independent of the companion note.} The companion note~\citep{BrilliantStrange2026} reported a lepton-derived quantity matching $m_s$ at a lepton-derived scale. The present paper reports a quark-internal relation at a lepton-derived scale ($m_\tau$). Both observations involve lepton masses entering the characterization of a quark-sector quantity, and it is plausible that they are two facets of a common structural relation between the charged-lepton sector and the quark mass spectrum. We do not develop this possibility here; it is the subject of future work.

\paragraph{Not robust to arbitrary scheme choice.} The $\sim 10^{-5}$ closure is specific to the $\overline{\text{MS}}$ scheme with the charm evaluation scale $\mu = m_\tau$. Converting to a uniform pole-mass triple or to alternative $\overline{\text{MS}}$ scale assignments degrades the closure, as discussed in Section~\ref{sec:error_budget}. This is consistent with the interpretation that the observation picks out a specific scheme-and-scale combination, not a scheme-independent identity, and we present it as such.

\section{Discussion and Conclusions}
\label{sec:discussion}

\paragraph{Relation to the companion note.} The companion note~\citep{BrilliantStrange2026} reports that a lepton-derived quantity $\mathcal{F}^2$, the squared outer Soddy curvature of the Koide-saturating lepton triple, matches $m_s^{\overline{\text{MS}}}$ at $\mu_\star = \sum m_\ell$ within current lattice precision. The present paper reports that an intrinsic Koide closure over the heavy quark triple $(c, b, t)$ reaches $\sim 10^{-5}$ when $m_c$ is evaluated at $\mu = m_\tau$. The two observations share the feature that a lepton-sector scale---$\sum m_\ell \approx 1883$~MeV in the first case, $m_\tau = 1776.93$~MeV in the second---enters the characterization of a quark-sector quantity to an accuracy that is, in both cases, much tighter than the general landscape of nearby scale choices. The two scales are numerically close (differing by $\approx 6\%$) but are not equivalent: the first is the sum of all three lepton masses, the second is the single heaviest. Whether their proximity is incidental or structural is not something we can resolve at current precision.

\paragraph{Relation to Rivero's $(s,c,b)$ construction.} Rivero's 2011 note~\citep{Rivero2011} reported a Koide-type closure for the $(s, c, b)$ triple with $-\sqrt{m_s}$ at approximately the $2\%$ level, and developed the chained-``waterfall'' construction. The present observation is complementary rather than competing: it concerns a different triple ($(c, b, t)$ rather than $(s, c, b)$), with all three roots positive (no $-\sqrt{}$ convention), at a much tighter closure ($\sim 10^{-5}$ rather than $2\%$), and at a specific renormalization scale ($\mu_c = m_\tau$) that, to our knowledge, has not been tested before in the quark-sector Koide literature. If both observations are signal, they are fragments of a common structure; if both are coincidence, they are fragments of a common coincidence. We have no mechanism for distinguishing these at present.

\paragraph{The principal open question.} Why $\mu = m_\tau$? The observation is sharp in scale: neighboring choices degrade the closure by two to three orders of magnitude, and the $1\sigma$ window in $\mu$ around $m_\tau$ is narrow compared to the range of natural scales in this regime. Any eventual explanation of the observation must account for the specific preference for $m_\tau$ as the charm evaluation scale; a derivation that gave only an approximate preference for ``some scale in the $1$--$2$~GeV range'' would not reproduce the tightness of the observed closure. We offer no such derivation and make no conjecture as to which class of explanations would eventually produce one.

\paragraph{Author's tentative interpretation.} The author's own reading of this observation, offered as speculation rather than argument, is the same as the one offered in the companion note: numerical regularities of this kind are best understood as shadows of underlying algebraic structure, as representations in a particular frame (here, renormalization-group evolution at a specific scale) of relations that are themselves primarily algebraic rather than dynamical. On this reading, the Koide condition is an algebraic identity that holds over the heavy quark triple in some natural variable, and the specific scale $\mu = m_\tau$ is the scale at which the observable $\overline{\text{MS}}$ masses happen to coincide with the natural variable. What that natural variable is, and why it corresponds to $\overline{\text{MS}}$-at-$m_\tau$ rather than to any other evaluation, is unknown. The author makes no case for this reading and does not ask the reader to accept it; the three possible interpretations enumerated in the companion note---geometric, dynamical, coincidental---apply here as well, and any preference among them is extra-scientific at the present level of evidence.

\paragraph{Conclusions.} We have reported that the Koide relation $Q = 2/3$ holds for the heavy quark triple $(c, b, t)$ to approximately $10^{-5}$ when the charm mass is evaluated at the renormalization scale $\mu = m_\tau$, in contrast to neighboring scale choices which degrade the closure by two to three orders of magnitude. The observation is stable under input-uncertainty propagation, sharp in scale, distinct from previous quark-sector Koide constructions, and consistent across Koide-rotation cross-checks. The null-model Monte Carlo conditioned on heavy-quark Koide-saturating triples gives a baseline hit fraction of [VALUE]\%, stable across the priors and scale rules tested. We make no claim of mechanism, derivation, or prediction. We flag the preference for $\mu = m_\tau$ as the principal open theoretical question raised by the observation, and we present the result as a precise numerical regularity whose theoretical status, if any, remains open.

\section*{Computational Note}

Central values, running computations, scale scans, rotation cross-checks, and null-model Monte Carlos reported in this paper are reproducible from the version-pinned GitHub repository at commit \texttt{[HASH]}~\citep{RepoHeavy}. Four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ running is performed via \texttt{CRunDec}~\citep{CRunDec} with $\alpha_s(M_Z) = 0.1180$ and flavor thresholds at $m_c(m_c) = [\text{VALUE}]$~GeV and $m_b(m_b) = [\text{VALUE}]$~GeV. Input masses are the FLAG 2024 $N_f = 2+1+1$ values for $m_c$ and $m_b$ and the PDG 2024 value for $m_t$. For the null-model sampler, candidate heavy-quark triples are drawn under four priors and two scale rules as described in Section~\ref{sec:null_prior}, with the same oversampling-to-valid-count architecture as the companion note; archived outputs are in \texttt{results/heavy\_null.json} at the cited commit. Total runtime for the full robustness analysis is under [VALUE] on a laptop.

\section*{Author's Note}

This paper is the second in a short sequence. The companion note~\citep{BrilliantStrange2026} reports the Soddy-curvature observation on the lepton side. A third paper in preparation will discuss whether the two observations, together with additional structural placements of the light quarks, admit a common representational framing; the present paper stands on its own and does not depend on the third for its interpretation.

